WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.760
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.110 --> 00:00:08.039
CHANGDRA RAM: I'm
someone who, I think,

00:00:08.039 --> 00:00:11.010
always just grew up
loving two things--

00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:15.040
that was food, and magazines,
and books, so food and writing.

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:17.100
And so I wound up--

00:00:17.100 --> 00:00:20.340
I'm the Editor of "Plate," which
is a food magazine for chefs.

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:24.090
But it seems like a very
well thought-out plan,

00:00:24.090 --> 00:00:27.750
but I did study
journalism in undergrad,

00:00:27.750 --> 00:00:32.110
and did a lot of
writing in that time.

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:33.780
And then I kind of
said, well, screw it.

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:35.238
I'm going to go to
culinary school.

00:00:35.238 --> 00:00:36.800
And I'm going to
go all in on that.

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:40.020
So I went to New York to the
Culinary Institute of America,

00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:44.844
and worked for a caterer there
doing all kinds of events.

00:00:44.844 --> 00:00:46.260
And she had a
prepared food store.

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:47.970
And that was exactly
what I wanted to do.

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:50.010
And thank god I worked for her.

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:52.530
So I learned that that
was exactly what I did not

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:53.830
want to do.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:58.040
And so I cooked in restaurants
and did some consulting,

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:02.160
culinary consulting work,
and then found my way back

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:06.120
into writing, and so was
working as a freelance food

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:08.370
writer, and kind
of happily being

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:12.080
able to provide this perspective
of what it's like to cook

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:14.040
and to work in restaurants.

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:16.860
And then with
"Plates", since we're

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:19.150
a food magazine for
chefs, it works out,

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:23.070
because I'm able to
better understand

00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:25.890
what chefs are going through,
what they're looking for,

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:29.220
the difference between avocado
toast as a trend for consumers

00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:33.420
as opposed to what they want to
have in the kitchen that works.

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:36.812
And then I get to hang out
with cool people like Bill.

00:01:36.812 --> 00:01:40.143
BILL KIM: And she travels how
many days out of the year?

00:01:40.143 --> 00:01:43.170
Probably like 200.

00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:46.500
CHANGDRA RAM: Well, and
actually, the genesis

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:52.080
of this book took place on a
bus in the middle of nowhere

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:57.240
in Australia, somewhere
between, I don't know--

00:01:57.240 --> 00:01:59.759
BILL KIM: Brisbane
and Melbourne, right?

00:01:59.759 --> 00:02:02.300
CHANGDRA RAM: Yeah, somewhere
between Brisbane and Melbourne,

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.550
Bill and his wife, Yvonne,
joined me on a trip

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:08.267
to learn all about Australia.

00:02:08.267 --> 00:02:09.850
I was asked to bring
some chefs there.

00:02:09.850 --> 00:02:13.360
So that's when the-- that was
like the germ of the idea.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:13.950
So--

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:14.370
BILL KIM: Here we are.

00:02:14.370 --> 00:02:15.536
CHANGDRA RAM: How about you?

00:02:15.536 --> 00:02:16.980
BILL KIM: Me?

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:20.680
So my journey
started from Korea.

00:02:20.680 --> 00:02:26.130
I was-- I moved here when
I was seven, not by choice.

00:02:26.130 --> 00:02:29.820
My parents wanted to give
us a better quality of life,

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:31.640
so we moved.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:37.230
And the thing that I ask my
parents, like, why didn't when

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:39.355
we, when we had the
layaway in LA and Hawaii,

00:02:39.355 --> 00:02:42.820
why did we not stop at
those places and live there?

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:48.450
So we ended up here
in 1977, in Chicago,

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:50.730
with the blizzard in February.

00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:54.690
So that was my harsh
reality, that I

00:02:54.690 --> 00:02:59.940
was going to live here, and
be here for probably, what,

00:02:59.940 --> 00:03:04.450
30 years, growing up, going
to grade school, high school.

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:06.450
Went to two culinary schools.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:08.820
I was fortunate enough I
found something I really

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:11.880
love to do at a very early age.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:15.060
And I really wanted to learn
the foundation of cooking,

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:17.430
which was not Korean back then.

00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:18.730
It was French cuisine.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:22.950
So I spent my time learning
about the foundation

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:27.270
of cooking, then
took me to Atlanta,

00:03:27.270 --> 00:03:30.520
worked for a French
gentleman down there.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:36.990
Then I came up for Chicago,
because I missed home deeply.

00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:41.430
I'm a huge sports fan, and
I know today's draft day.

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:44.610
So we have to make sure that
the Bears pick the right person.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.940
I had two people that
I went to go spend

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:53.170
a day, or trail, or shadow.

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:56.220
And they both kind of
pointed at this restaurant.

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:57.440
It was at a townhouse.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:01.170
It was 816 West Armitage.

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.690
And it was a restaurant
called Charlie Trotter's.

00:04:03.690 --> 00:04:07.540
And basically, both of these
chefs had their own restaurant,

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:11.500
but they said if I were you,
I would go to this restaurant.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:14.960
And I had no clue what this
restaurant's all about.

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:18.630
But when I got there,
my world really

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:24.660
changed, and really helped
propel me to what I know now.

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:30.570
Because it really-- that was
the focal point of cuisine

00:04:30.570 --> 00:04:33.354
back in the early '90s.

00:04:33.354 --> 00:04:34.770
I was fortunate
enough to be there

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:39.230
for about three and a half
years the first time around.

00:04:39.230 --> 00:04:42.780
And we were voted the number
one restaurant in the country

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:44.760
back then.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:48.750
We had a table in the kitchen.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:53.160
We had a $250,000
Rolls-Royce of a stove

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:56.820
that was one piece, that
was built in Lyon, France.

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:02.550
You could eat food off
the floor, if it need be.

00:05:02.550 --> 00:05:05.300
Every hour within
the hour there's, we

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:06.470
call it a sweep and a mop.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:11.750
And basically, we would have
the new recruits or new cooks

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:16.180
that came in, basically, how
you handled the mop and a broom

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:19.440
would tell you how
that person works.

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:22.400
That was an inside
joke between all of us.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:27.560
But that really made me
see outside of Chicago.

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:28.880
So I got to travel.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:34.880
I got to eat it three-star
Michelin restaurants.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:35.730
I was 26.

00:05:35.730 --> 00:05:36.650
I didn't know.

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:39.000
I had-- I tell
Chandra all the time--

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.940
one sport jacket, not a suit.

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:42.110
I had one sport jacket.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:44.780
And Charlie said, I think you're
going to need a couple more,

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:48.870
because we're going to go and
do a book signing in France,

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:52.100
meet the French media,
go to Switzerland.

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:55.560
And I've never traveled
outside of Chicago.

00:05:55.560 --> 00:06:00.650
And when I came back,
I knew I had to leave.

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:03.960
I had to see different
parts of the world.

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:06.620
So I left for 10 years
on the east coast,

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:08.600
and got to experience it.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:12.800
But same thing happened,
where I missed home again.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:16.670
This time, for 10
years, I had my watch

00:06:16.670 --> 00:06:20.610
and my clocks set on Midwestern
time-- never changed it.

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:22.940
And I knew I was going
to come back home.

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:24.740
And I came back.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:27.950
My second tour of
duty at Trotter's, I

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:31.010
was named the chef de cuisine.

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:32.330
But it wasn't the same.

00:06:32.330 --> 00:06:38.510
It wasn't that tunnel-vision
kid 10 years ago working there.

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:39.720
And I'd seen the world.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:42.660
And I'm just, like, I
have to open my own place.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:47.480
And when it was time for me
to do that, it wasn't what

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:48.780
I was trained to do.

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:51.900
I wanted to do something
that was more meaningful,

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:56.270
which meant wanted to
do food that was closer

00:06:56.270 --> 00:06:58.140
to me, who I was as a person.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:01.050
My family owned dry cleaners.

00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:03.770
I always say dry cleaners,
but they only owned one.

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:07.460
My parents washed people's
clothes for 35 years.

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:10.010
And I seen how hard they worked.

00:07:10.010 --> 00:07:15.500
So I always told myself,
if I got educated here,

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:16.970
did something that
I really wanted

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:20.180
to do, there's no way in hell
I was not going to succeed,

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:23.690
because they did something
they didn't want to do.

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:24.790
They sacrificed for us.

00:07:24.790 --> 00:07:29.240
So that was a synthesis of us.

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:31.640
We said, we will
build this restaurant,

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:33.420
and we will make it work.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:37.730
And the irony is, when we
built the first restaurant

00:07:37.730 --> 00:07:40.670
of our own, it was
in a strip mall--

00:07:40.670 --> 00:07:44.000
dry cleaners and a laundry mat.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.020
So we were in 1,000
square-foot place.

00:07:48.020 --> 00:07:52.250
And we opened in 2008,
so it's been 10 years.

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:55.160
But the economy was
going like this.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:57.500
All the people that
I have worked with

00:07:57.500 --> 00:08:00.834
or my friends who have
the higher end restaurant,

00:08:00.834 --> 00:08:02.750
they were suffering,
because it was that time.

00:08:02.750 --> 00:08:07.220
And I really thought
the market was missing.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:09.260
You had the high
end places, and you

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:12.500
had the fast-food
restaurants, but there

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.582
was nothing in between.

00:08:14.582 --> 00:08:19.280
I'm just, like, why can't food
not be expensive, but still

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:21.240
be really, really good?

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:23.960
And that's when we
opened up Urban Belly.

00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:26.240
It's counter service.

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:28.224
Nothing's over $13.

00:08:28.224 --> 00:08:32.179
And we basically said,
if it's flavorful,

00:08:32.179 --> 00:08:36.409
it's accessible, affordable
to everybody, hey,

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.990
if I fail on that, I'm OK.

00:08:38.990 --> 00:08:40.850
Because when we first--

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:43.700
when we opened up that
restaurant, I'd lived my dream.

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:46.160
That was everything
that I could wish for.

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:48.890
And I always tell somebody, if
I get hit by a car tomorrow,

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:50.330
I lived my dream.

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:53.950
So then on top of
that, we opened up

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:56.900
Belly Shack, then bellyQ.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:58.670
We have our sauce line.

00:08:58.670 --> 00:08:59.780
Now we have a book.

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:02.150
I mean, I pinch
myself every day,

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:06.590
because it's all the things
I've thought about doing.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:08.960
And were actually doing it.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:12.620
And with her help, I
mean, with my wife's help,

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:16.790
it's just I surrounded
myself with ladies of power.

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:19.850
And it's just like I just
have to just kind of dream,

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:22.790
and think, and they
did do the pushing.

00:09:22.790 --> 00:09:26.252
And they've done very well.

00:09:26.252 --> 00:09:28.460
SPEAKER: So when you talk
a little about the impetus,

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:31.160
and your background, one
thing I was curious about

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:34.220
is what inspired you,
even at the beginning

00:09:34.220 --> 00:09:38.480
and as you were growing up,
that gave you that passion

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:40.580
to go after going
to culinary school,

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:42.440
just at the starting point?

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:45.860
BILL KIM: Well,
when you're young,

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:48.050
especially when you're
from another country,

00:09:48.050 --> 00:09:51.110
you just want to fit in.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:52.640
I had a Korean name.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:55.010
It was very hard to pronounce.

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:56.150
And I was--

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:59.180
I knew when B came
around in the alphabet,

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:02.099
I'm just, like, oh, I need
to go hide, because they're

00:10:02.099 --> 00:10:03.140
going to make fun of you.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:04.200
So--

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:05.700
CHANGDRA RAM: You
have to tell them.

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:07.080
BILL KIM: It's Bum-Suk.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:12.320
Then my brother's first
name is Yoo-Suk, so Yoo-Suk,

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:13.890
or you suck--

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:15.740
I mean, that was just--

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:18.650
it was so, like, come on.

00:10:18.650 --> 00:10:20.870
CHANGDRA RAM: Bill told
me this the day before we

00:10:20.870 --> 00:10:22.130
had to turn in the manuscript.

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:23.588
And I was, like,
oh, my god, I have

00:10:23.588 --> 00:10:26.090
to go back and rewrite the
entire introduction just

00:10:26.090 --> 00:10:27.200
so we can get this in.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:29.740
But it's such a
universal experience.

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:33.840
If you have a name that's
reflective of another country,

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:36.680
you totally remember being
a little kid in school,

00:10:36.680 --> 00:10:39.874
knowing, OK, yeah, my
name's about to come up,

00:10:39.874 --> 00:10:41.290
and they don't
know how to say it.

00:10:41.290 --> 00:10:41.990
BILL KIM: Yeah.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:43.740
CHANGDRA RAM: I don't
know how you did it.

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:49.260
BILL KIM: So the reason
why we did the restaurant

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:53.490
that we were so driven to do,
because for selfish reasons,

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:56.730
I wanted a restaurant
of both cultures.

00:10:56.730 --> 00:11:00.870
I wanted-- I didn't want to eat
rice three times a day, which

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:02.370
was what I was
accustomed to doing.

00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:04.440
And I used to go
every Friday, I would

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.450
go to my friend's,
Joe McDermott's house,

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:10.050
because I knew every Friday
was pizza at their house.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:11.276
So I loved that.

00:11:11.276 --> 00:11:12.900
And I used to go to
Tony Bruno's house,

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:16.230
because I knew it was Prince
spaghetti day on Wednesday.

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:18.289
And I knew what I
was going to get.

00:11:18.289 --> 00:11:20.580
At my house, you never knew
what you were going to get,

00:11:20.580 --> 00:11:23.670
because we probably ate the
leftovers from the two days

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:24.460
before.

00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:27.040
So you're eating the
same thing all the time.

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:30.060
So as we thought
about what it meant

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:32.100
to open up your
restaurant, I think

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:36.390
this is something that a lot of
the chefs sometimes miss out.

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:37.530
It's not the concept.

00:11:37.530 --> 00:11:39.930
It's who you are as
a person, and how

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.270
you want to express
yourself in the food.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:43.830
That's being genuine.

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:44.940
It's not the concept.

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:47.460
It's not how well
you could cook.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:49.500
Like, what's from
your heart, and you've

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:51.660
got to let that show
on the plate of food

00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:52.860
that you're cooking.

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:56.130
So what we are cooking when
we opened up the restaurant,

00:11:56.130 --> 00:11:59.280
it's all the things
that I wanted to eat.

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:01.560
It's what we prepared at home.

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:03.620
But I wanted to elevate it.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:05.520
Like, my mom used
to do fried rice,

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:07.060
but she made it with Crisco.

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:10.230
And she used 10 pounds of rice.

00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:13.610
And we had it for
months in the microwave.

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:14.980
And we would take it out.

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:18.550
And we used to have a stick,
because there is tons of Crisco

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:19.270
there.

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:21.960
So we said we're going
to do fried rice.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:25.529
But we also made dumplings
at the house, so we did--

00:12:25.529 --> 00:12:27.070
we're going to
elevate the dumplings.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:31.320
And the dumplings are going to
be five different skins, five

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:33.850
different unique flavors.

00:12:33.850 --> 00:12:36.180
Then on top of
that, Urban Belly,

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:39.120
people call it a ramen shop.

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:41.080
But if you really
look at our menu,

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:42.960
we only have one damn ramen.

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:45.030
So no, it's not a ramen shop.

00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:49.410
It's a noodle shop with five
different kinds of noodles.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:54.030
Because it takes-- to me,
when you go spend the time,

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:56.610
and learn some of the
things that I did,

00:12:56.610 --> 00:13:00.210
it's easy to just do ramen.

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:07.285
But when you start putting
rice cakes, rice noodles, udon,

00:13:07.285 --> 00:13:11.860
chow fun, it's all these
things that it's there.

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:15.420
It's for you to kind of go,
and put some skills in there,

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:16.980
and make it tasty.

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:19.920
So it's for selfish reasons.

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:24.160
So we did something
that I love eating.

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:26.040
But we wanted to elevate it.

00:13:26.040 --> 00:13:30.090
So competition-wise,
I didn't want

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:32.040
people to be able to
do some of the things,

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:34.320
because I have a
different experience

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:37.410
than a lot of the
other shops in Chicago,

00:13:37.410 --> 00:13:40.320
and wanted to kind
of put our stamp,

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:43.740
and I wanted to bring to
the city something totally

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:45.590
different that people
are not accustomed to.

00:13:48.338 --> 00:13:50.404
SPEAKER: Knowing you
spent time in fine dining,

00:13:50.404 --> 00:13:52.070
working for Charlie
Trotter, and knowing

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:53.990
there's lots of alumni
of Charlie Trotter who

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:56.990
have gone on in Chicago
to start restaurants,

00:13:56.990 --> 00:14:03.380
how would you say being from the
Midwest, and your wife's Puerto

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:06.446
Rican descent, how
that has influenced?

00:14:06.446 --> 00:14:07.570
Because it is very genuine.

00:14:07.570 --> 00:14:08.550
We've been to the restaurant.

00:14:08.550 --> 00:14:09.841
We've tasted a lot of the food.

00:14:09.841 --> 00:14:13.220
And it feels so natural.

00:14:13.220 --> 00:14:14.180
it's truly amazing.

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:15.680
But what was that
process like, even

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:18.260
just starting the
restaurant, and making

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:22.310
that move to Urban Belly?

00:14:22.310 --> 00:14:25.820
BILL KIM: Yeah, I think the
thing that we kept on saying,

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:28.490
we want to start taking away.

00:14:28.490 --> 00:14:33.140
Less is more, which meant
when you work in fine dining,

00:14:33.140 --> 00:14:38.210
there there's a lot of layers
of the hierarchy, who's who,

00:14:38.210 --> 00:14:42.920
and who has
seniority, or we need

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:45.140
to have this type of service.

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:46.610
We just said, you know what?

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:48.864
You come, free parking.

00:14:48.864 --> 00:14:50.780
You don't have to pay
for alcohol because it's

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:53.060
BYOB five years ago.

00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:54.800
And you see the menu.

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:55.640
You order.

00:14:55.640 --> 00:15:00.440
We just took all the
things out of dining,

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:01.850
what people understood.

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:05.810
And it was basically to
primitive-- here's food.

00:15:05.810 --> 00:15:06.510
You pay.

00:15:06.510 --> 00:15:07.010
You order.

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:08.176
We're bringing you the food.

00:15:08.176 --> 00:15:09.290
And that was it.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:11.210
If you don't like it, too bad.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:15.230
But it was all
about giving it back

00:15:15.230 --> 00:15:18.275
to the customers, which meant
you don't have to valet.

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:23.670
You don't have to tip
if you don't want to.

00:15:23.670 --> 00:15:24.930
And here it is.

00:15:24.930 --> 00:15:27.240
Here's the food, and this
what we're going to do.

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:28.656
You're going to
get great service.

00:15:28.656 --> 00:15:32.000
I always said you could do two
things-- you could say thank

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:33.770
you and hello to a customer.

00:15:33.770 --> 00:15:36.320
That costs nobody any money.

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:38.990
If we could do that,
that's something

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:40.490
that anybody could do.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:48.470
And going into the
culture of my wife and I,

00:15:48.470 --> 00:15:51.740
it's all natural, because
we always like this--

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:53.270
when we do food,
we like to say we

00:15:53.270 --> 00:15:55.620
like to tell the love
story through food,

00:15:55.620 --> 00:16:00.620
which means when I met my
wife, I'd never had plantains.

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:03.650
But when I had it,
I'm just, like, wow.

00:16:03.650 --> 00:16:07.220
How can I put this into my food?

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:09.770
And I wanted to not
because she's my wife.

00:16:09.770 --> 00:16:11.420
It's something that
I've never had.

00:16:11.420 --> 00:16:14.330
So we do a dish at bellyQ now.

00:16:14.330 --> 00:16:15.920
It's called mofongo.

00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:20.210
So it's plaintains that is
boiled instead of fried.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:23.860
So I try to take the dish apart.

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:27.860
First, the traditional way
is you take pork skins,

00:16:27.860 --> 00:16:28.760
chicharrones.

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:33.800
You take garlic,
almost like a mojo.

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:36.650
And you just smash
it until you just

00:16:36.650 --> 00:16:40.760
get this mashed plantation.

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:43.890
Changdra hates this, but
I use tofu cream cheese.

00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:47.120
That is something
that I like using,

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:52.430
because it adds richness,
without being super heavy.

00:16:52.430 --> 00:16:54.080
Then instead of
adding chicharrones,

00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:56.740
we add crispy tortillas.

00:16:56.740 --> 00:16:59.690
Then we add our version
of chimichurri or mojo.

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:03.710
Then we make this, like, mashed
plantation with chimichurri,

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:06.260
so it has the flavor of mofongo.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:09.500
It's not traditional,
but on top of that,

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:11.960
we add kimchi salsa
on top of the--

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:13.680
I call it mashed plantains.

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:15.980
So it kind of gives you a kick.

00:17:15.980 --> 00:17:17.690
But it all goes well together.

00:17:17.690 --> 00:17:21.130
Because we don't just say this
is what we're going to do.

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:23.750
We actually taste it, make
sure it goes well together.

00:17:23.750 --> 00:17:26.430
Then we serve pork
and plantation chips.

00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:29.450
So it's a harmonious
way of doing it.

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:33.720
But my wife definitely has
an influence on my cooking,

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:40.070
and I kind of have influence
on her of cleaning.

00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:42.430
But she won't let me
clean up the house.

00:17:42.430 --> 00:17:45.860
She's, like, no, you cannot
use this sponge for this.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:47.380
I'm just, like, come on.

00:17:47.380 --> 00:17:48.420
Just let me clean.

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:49.430
She won't let me do it.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:54.530
I always tell her before
she goes shopping,

00:17:54.530 --> 00:17:57.170
you've got to take an
inventory of cleaning products.

00:17:57.170 --> 00:17:59.650
Because she always buys
double of everything.

00:17:59.650 --> 00:18:01.070
Stop.

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:02.720
It's not going to go bad.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:05.414
You've got to take
inventory before you go.

00:18:05.414 --> 00:18:07.580
SPEAKER: Cleaning products
are definitely important.

00:18:07.580 --> 00:18:09.920
I'm thinking about that
in my own home life,

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:15.800
and yeah, the sponge
struggle is real, very real.

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:18.207
So tell us a little bit
more about the book.

00:18:18.207 --> 00:18:20.540
Just in describing the food,
I think a lot of our mouths

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:21.290
are watering.

00:18:21.290 --> 00:18:24.530
And just a quick note for
everyone here, our happy hour,

00:18:24.530 --> 00:18:26.360
our IFFY event
afterwards, we're actually

00:18:26.360 --> 00:18:28.040
going to have some
dishes from the book.

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:30.449
So save room.

00:18:30.449 --> 00:18:32.240
But that in mind, tell
us a little bit more

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:33.710
about the book and the process.

00:18:34.735 --> 00:18:36.410
BILL KIM: Changdra.

00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:40.640
CHANGDRA RAM: Well, the
book came together really

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:44.580
as a reflection of a lot of
what Bill's been talking about,

00:18:44.580 --> 00:18:46.790
which is how he
runs his restaurant.

00:18:46.790 --> 00:18:50.120
And so when we first sat down
and started talking about this,

00:18:50.120 --> 00:18:53.650
he said, look, here's
what I want to do.

00:18:53.650 --> 00:18:55.700
Bill trained in French kitchens.

00:18:55.700 --> 00:18:57.950
I went to culinary
school when it

00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:00.949
was kind of all French, all
sort of old-school European.

00:19:00.949 --> 00:19:02.990
And so we're both very
used to the idea of mother

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:04.940
sauces, these
sauces that you use,

00:19:04.940 --> 00:19:06.554
and you just create variations.

00:19:06.554 --> 00:19:07.970
And that's how you
make everything

00:19:07.970 --> 00:19:09.830
in classical French cooking.

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:13.430
He created the master
sauces for Korean barbecue.

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:17.600
And so it's seven different
sauces and three spice rubs.

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:20.840
And you create those.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:24.200
I have tubs of them in my--
small, little tubs of them

00:19:24.200 --> 00:19:25.320
in my freezer.

00:19:25.320 --> 00:19:27.236
And I just make them,
throw them in there.

00:19:27.236 --> 00:19:28.860
And then when I want
to make something,

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:30.980
I just pull out, OK, I
need half a cup of this.

00:19:30.980 --> 00:19:34.150
I need three tablespoons
of that, mix them up.

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:37.370
So you take these seven
sauces, three spice rubs,

00:19:37.370 --> 00:19:39.680
use them all sorts of
different combinations.

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:42.240
And that's how you make
everything in the book.

00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:44.610
So it's how he runs
his restaurants.

00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:46.820
It's incredibly efficient.

00:19:46.820 --> 00:19:49.700
It allows people
who maybe don't have

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:52.590
a ton of culinary
experience, training,

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:55.250
it allows them to learn
a skill, because it's

00:19:55.250 --> 00:19:56.400
very easy to do that.

00:19:56.400 --> 00:19:59.532
But it's also really cool,
because so many people--

00:19:59.532 --> 00:20:01.490
it's only been a week
since the book came out--

00:20:01.490 --> 00:20:04.430
but so many people are,
like, this is so easy.

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:07.760
I cannot believe on a Tuesday
night I'm actually able to make

00:20:07.760 --> 00:20:08.900
this food.

00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:11.900
And one thing I really love
about it is all of the things

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:15.290
that Bill was talking about,
like going to hang out with his

00:20:15.290 --> 00:20:20.150
Italian friends after school
or having a Puerto Rican wife,

00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:23.470
and I think more importantly,
a Puerto Rican mother-in-law--

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:25.302
BILL KIM: Yes, my
wife doesn't cook.

00:20:25.302 --> 00:20:27.010
CHANGDRA RAM: That's
why she married you.

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:27.760
BILL KIM: Yeah.

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:30.470
CHANGDRA RAM: But all
of those influences,

00:20:30.470 --> 00:20:34.220
time working at Charlie
Trotter's, his time

00:20:34.220 --> 00:20:37.520
working for Jean Banchet in
Atlanta, all those things

00:20:37.520 --> 00:20:38.690
come through in the book.

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:44.120
So you see there's a sauce
we called a Korican sauce.

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:49.790
And it's his Korean/Puerto
Rican master sauce that you use.

00:20:49.790 --> 00:20:52.100
And you can mix it up.

00:20:52.100 --> 00:20:55.400
And you can use it on
any kind of protein.

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:58.420
We did that with a
turkey and with the pork,

00:20:58.420 --> 00:21:00.150
I think, in the book.

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:02.990
And so it's really
cool to just see

00:21:02.990 --> 00:21:05.030
all these different
flavors, and see

00:21:05.030 --> 00:21:08.670
how Bill's experience traveling
to a different country

00:21:08.670 --> 00:21:12.710
would yield a new
sauce that you combine

00:21:12.710 --> 00:21:16.310
in a ton of different ways, and
make all these great dishes.

00:21:16.310 --> 00:21:18.050
And then you combine
everything again,

00:21:18.050 --> 00:21:20.815
and you make-- we have an
entire chapter on leftovers.

00:21:20.815 --> 00:21:22.940
Because we're both Asian,
and we do not waste food.

00:21:25.502 --> 00:21:26.960
BILL KIM: How to
Kung Fu it, right?

00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:27.740
CHANGDRA RAM: Yes.

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:30.980
SPEAKER: I might have to ask
you more about that in a minute.

00:21:30.980 --> 00:21:33.620
I have to say that
for me personally,

00:21:33.620 --> 00:21:35.330
I don't do a lot of
cooking in the home.

00:21:35.330 --> 00:21:36.150
I think there are
some people here

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:38.140
who might be able
to attest to that.

00:21:38.140 --> 00:21:41.480
And when looking at the recipes,
they seem very accessible.

00:21:41.480 --> 00:21:43.997
And being in
Chicago, the weather

00:21:43.997 --> 00:21:45.080
is finally getting better.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:49.190
People are beginning to consider
dusting off their grills, which

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:50.600
is pretty exciting.

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:52.040
And we want to put them to use.

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.498
Could you maybe tell us a little
about your favorite dishes

00:21:54.498 --> 00:21:58.400
from the cookbook, or just
go-to things when for you

00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:00.620
personally, when
you're in a hurry,

00:22:00.620 --> 00:22:02.740
or when you want to
entertain people, things

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:04.950
you like to cook?

00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:07.450
BILL KIM: A personal
favorite in the recipe--

00:22:07.450 --> 00:22:09.950
it's like, what is
your signature dish?

00:22:09.950 --> 00:22:12.320
Well, the story that I love--

00:22:12.320 --> 00:22:16.380
when we were young, we
couldn't afford a grill.

00:22:16.380 --> 00:22:19.580
And the public parks, it's
called "forest preserves"

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:20.780
in Chicago.

00:22:20.780 --> 00:22:23.540
So they would have free grills.

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:27.920
So we would go as a family
on Sundays after church.

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:30.350
And we would go have
one of those grills.

00:22:30.350 --> 00:22:32.340
And we put charcoal in there.

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:34.910
And as soon as we put
the meat on that's

00:22:34.910 --> 00:22:38.710
been marinating overnight,
it's one of the recipes,

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:41.540
and strangers would
come, because they would

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:44.000
smell the Korean barbecue.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.770
And that's one of the moments
in my life that I remember.

00:22:48.770 --> 00:22:52.190
Because now, it breaks
down barrier who

00:22:52.190 --> 00:22:54.760
you are, what color you are.

00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:55.880
It's food.

00:22:55.880 --> 00:23:01.490
And it just opens the gateway
to people trying something new

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:03.140
in somebody else's culture.

00:23:03.140 --> 00:23:05.000
So that's, like, wow.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.290
That was the moment.

00:23:07.290 --> 00:23:15.950
And just doing this kind of
food, it's easy, accessible.

00:23:15.950 --> 00:23:20.350
And I think a lot of times when
people are cooking Asian food,

00:23:20.350 --> 00:23:22.820
they're so intimidated.

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:28.880
So we made it very simple for
people to go get ingredients.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:32.690
And the last week,
I've been getting

00:23:32.690 --> 00:23:35.210
videos and Instagrams of
people actually cooking out

00:23:35.210 --> 00:23:36.380
of the book.

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:40.420
So there's moments
where I'm, like, not--

00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:42.320
it's supposed to be
Korean chili flakes,

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:45.050
not chili flakes that you put.

00:23:45.050 --> 00:23:49.280
So that's like triple
the spice it needs.

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:51.200
But you know what it is?

00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:55.190
We have to all understand
that now more than ever,

00:23:55.190 --> 00:23:58.400
there is no border
around what we do.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:01.610
So we like to say we're
cooking without borders,

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:07.100
which means you don't have to
be an expert, but I studied it.

00:24:07.100 --> 00:24:08.700
I wanted to do this.

00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:12.380
But always, when you're in a
category, when we first opened,

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:15.620
people were, like, what
category do you want to be in?

00:24:15.620 --> 00:24:16.410
Is it Korean?

00:24:16.410 --> 00:24:19.896
Is it fusion-- and I hate the
word, "fusion," because, ugh.

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:24.380
Let it be.

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:25.340
It could be Asian.

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:28.220
And it could be
influences from all over.

00:24:28.220 --> 00:24:34.790
Because it really-- when I
look at Mexico, what they have,

00:24:34.790 --> 00:24:38.345
and what's in Asia--

00:24:38.345 --> 00:24:41.270
a water chestnut doesn't
have to be canned.

00:24:41.270 --> 00:24:44.150
But what can you find,
something that's here,

00:24:44.150 --> 00:24:45.770
that's similar in texture?

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:51.950
So I look to Latin
cuisine, you have jicama.

00:24:51.950 --> 00:24:55.370
And you get that same texture.

00:24:55.370 --> 00:24:58.380
And then you can go either way.

00:24:58.380 --> 00:25:01.370
And we use chili in
both parts of the world.

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:02.870
Cilantro is called coriander.

00:25:02.870 --> 00:25:06.350
So you could do that all over.

00:25:06.350 --> 00:25:09.500
And that's what draws
the inspiration for me

00:25:09.500 --> 00:25:13.310
to find the commonality
in all the cultures,

00:25:13.310 --> 00:25:14.930
and put it in our food.

00:25:14.930 --> 00:25:16.940
And hopefully, this
year, me and my wife

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:19.187
will get to go to Greece,
which I've never been to.

00:25:19.187 --> 00:25:21.020
But I know I'm going
to find something there

00:25:21.020 --> 00:25:22.850
that I'm going to
bring back, and it's

00:25:22.850 --> 00:25:24.020
going to go into my food.

00:25:24.020 --> 00:25:31.580
Because olive oil, limes,
lemons, things like that,

00:25:31.580 --> 00:25:35.750
those are haunting flavors
that I like to use in my food.

00:25:35.750 --> 00:25:37.880
SPEAKER: So we talk
about connectedness

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:42.200
and how you're creating
food without borders,

00:25:42.200 --> 00:25:46.070
technology is also a big factor
in breaking down barriers.

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:48.650
And would be curious, both from
the perspective of the book

00:25:48.650 --> 00:25:51.890
and also from the perspective
of your business as a chef

00:25:51.890 --> 00:25:55.150
and as a business owner, how
technology has helped you.

