she's here.

00:39:35.480 --> 00:39:39.060
And I talk to her probably
more than my wife,

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:44.040
and seeing what we
do, how we do it.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:45.230
It's a strategy.

00:39:45.230 --> 00:39:46.040
It really is.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:49.230
And food is a given.

00:39:49.230 --> 00:39:54.380
Now we have to be able
to have people know

00:39:54.380 --> 00:39:55.590
what it is that we're doing.

00:39:55.590 --> 00:40:01.310
But it is right up there,
probably as more important.

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:04.470
Because I believe food
should be a given.

00:40:04.470 --> 00:40:06.650
There should be
that's a standard.

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:08.450
Than everything else
we have to work at,

00:40:08.450 --> 00:40:11.601
and social media is right there.

00:40:11.601 --> 00:40:13.100
CHANGDRA RAM: And
we learned so much

00:40:13.100 --> 00:40:17.340
about what people wanted in a
cookbook from reading reviews.

00:40:17.340 --> 00:40:21.527
So I would-- you know when you
wake up at 4:00 in the morning,

00:40:21.527 --> 00:40:23.360
you're a little freaked
out about everything

00:40:23.360 --> 00:40:24.320
you've got going on?

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:26.460
I would do exactly what
you're not supposed to do,

00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:28.280
which is I would grab my phone.

00:40:28.280 --> 00:40:32.210
And I started reading Amazon
reader reviews, reviews

00:40:32.210 --> 00:40:38.150
on Food52, see what people were
saying about different grilling

00:40:38.150 --> 00:40:41.240
books, about Korean books,
about cookbooks in general,

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:45.260
and what kind of
issues they had.

00:40:45.260 --> 00:40:47.660
One of the things I
really love about our book

00:40:47.660 --> 00:40:53.120
is the fact that the recipes
for those seven sauces

00:40:53.120 --> 00:40:56.870
and the three spice rubs,
which are all very short,

00:40:56.870 --> 00:40:59.480
they were printed on
the inside back cover.

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:03.290
And that was a thing
I kept bringing up,

00:41:03.290 --> 00:41:08.330
because on Food52, so many
people commented about how they

00:41:08.330 --> 00:41:11.240
hated having to flip back
and forth in a cookbook

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:13.380
to find, oh, god,
there's a subrecipe.

00:41:13.380 --> 00:41:14.840
And it's on Page 36.

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:16.730
And now I've got
to find Page 36.

00:41:16.730 --> 00:41:19.370
And then I've got to
go back to Page 79

00:41:19.370 --> 00:41:21.110
to find the original recipe.

00:41:21.110 --> 00:41:22.520
So we kept working.

00:41:22.520 --> 00:41:25.770
It was a thing that we
brought up from the get-go

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:27.380
with our editor.

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:32.390
And Kelly, and Lizzie,
and Emma, the design team,

00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:35.030
they kept kind of figuring out,
saying, OK, well, maybe we'll

00:41:35.030 --> 00:41:35.900
do a big pull-out.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:38.630
And I was, one day, what if we
have different colored ribbons?

00:41:38.630 --> 00:41:40.220
And then she just texted
me back, and said,

00:41:40.220 --> 00:41:41.386
who's going to pay for that?

00:41:41.386 --> 00:41:42.540
And I was, like, OK.

00:41:42.540 --> 00:41:47.450
So then I came up with this
idea to print these base recipes

00:41:47.450 --> 00:41:49.810
on the inside cover, so you
don't have to flip around.

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:50.900
You can find them.

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:53.090
But that's something
I wouldn't have known,

00:41:53.090 --> 00:41:56.180
we wouldn't have known, to
even ask for and really push

00:41:56.180 --> 00:42:00.410
for had we not seen the
complaints on social media.

00:42:00.410 --> 00:42:02.160
So sometimes, it is
for good and not evil.

00:42:04.730 --> 00:42:05.550
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:42:05.550 --> 00:42:06.300
Thanks for coming.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:07.740
I have a couple of questions.

00:42:07.740 --> 00:42:10.202
The first one is, how do
you choose a recipe tester?

00:42:10.202 --> 00:42:11.660
And how much
influence do they have

00:42:11.660 --> 00:42:12.951
over the direction of the book?

00:42:16.062 --> 00:42:18.020
CHANGDRA RAM: I mean, we
were fortunate to have

00:42:18.020 --> 00:42:20.660
very good friends who were
starting a business where

00:42:20.660 --> 00:42:23.480
they were testing recipes.

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:27.860
But it's also equally
important to send the recipe

00:42:27.860 --> 00:42:32.000
to someone who doesn't know
you, ideally someone who doesn't

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:33.870
really know how to cook.

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:34.390
That's--

00:42:34.390 --> 00:42:35.375
AUDIENCE: I volunteer
as [INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:42:35.375 --> 00:42:35.660
CHANGDRA RAM: OK.

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:37.850
AUDIENCE: Just in case you
ever need someone in future.

00:42:37.850 --> 00:42:40.016
CHANGDRA RAM: Because you
want to know how someone--

00:42:40.016 --> 00:42:42.790
I mean, if Bill
hands me a recipe,

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:46.980
I have known him and his
food for years, and years,

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:48.070
and years.

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:51.460
And I cooked in restaurants.

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:53.070
And so I will--

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:54.870
someone who's very
well trained will

00:42:54.870 --> 00:42:57.810
start to automatically
fill in the blanks.

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:01.030
But you want
someone to say, hey,

00:43:01.030 --> 00:43:04.770
you've got me soaking
rice, and then cooking it.

00:43:04.770 --> 00:43:07.440
Am I cooking it in the
water I'm soaking it in?

00:43:07.440 --> 00:43:10.577
Or am I adding fresh water?

00:43:10.577 --> 00:43:11.910
And someone asked that question.

00:43:11.910 --> 00:43:13.960
I was, like, I would
never have thought,

00:43:13.960 --> 00:43:15.890
OK, now we're
adding that back in.

00:43:15.890 --> 00:43:18.030
BILL KIM: And it
was important for us

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:22.890
that people were using
a residential stove.

00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:26.130
Because obviously,
our commercial stuff

00:43:26.130 --> 00:43:29.190
is probably three
times as powerful.

00:43:29.190 --> 00:43:33.720
So it was very
important that they were

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:35.430
using that type of equipment.

00:43:35.430 --> 00:43:39.890
And also, we were
fortunate enough to--

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:44.460
our recipe testers,
one of them had kids,

00:43:44.460 --> 00:43:48.510
which I wanted to have,
because I would only

00:43:48.510 --> 00:43:50.410
cook for two at the house.

00:43:50.410 --> 00:43:52.380
And Changdra also.

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:53.850
So there was going
to be leftovers.

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:56.046
How they were going to use it?

00:43:56.046 --> 00:43:57.420
And they're, like,
the kids don't

00:43:57.420 --> 00:43:59.640
want to eat that broccoli
anymore, because they've

00:43:59.640 --> 00:44:01.290
been eating it for days.

00:44:01.290 --> 00:44:07.124
But we knew for six people,
this will be this much.

00:44:07.124 --> 00:44:10.860
And the thing that
we also wanted was we

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:15.270
wanted all the ingredients to
be accessible to the grocery

00:44:15.270 --> 00:44:18.180
store, not specialty markets.

00:44:18.180 --> 00:44:20.540
Because I think that's
another thing that I read,

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:23.280
that people just didn't want
to go to five different places

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:25.410
to get things for the recipe.

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:27.890
So it was very, very
important for us

00:44:27.890 --> 00:44:32.640
to be accessible to a
whole realm of people that

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:35.487
want to cook this type of food.

