00:46:20.550 --> 00:46:21.955
BILL KIM: You are.

00:46:21.955 --> 00:46:24.150
[INAUDIBLE] Just kidding.

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:28.125
SPEAKER: I think we have
one more question coming up.

00:46:28.125 --> 00:46:30.855
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:30.855 --> 00:46:33.438
I think one of the things that
you were talking about in terms

00:46:33.438 --> 00:46:39.835
of defining, almost, the type
of food or category of food,

00:46:39.835 --> 00:46:43.932
and you hating the word
"fusion," and then people also

00:46:43.932 --> 00:46:46.668
wanting something
super authentic, what's

00:46:46.668 --> 00:46:49.390
that kind of balance
like, and try and find

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:52.280
something that's
authentic, not fusion,

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:56.230
but still something that's
authentic to your restaurant?

00:46:56.230 --> 00:46:58.090
BILL KIM: Yeah.

00:46:58.090 --> 00:47:01.230
Did I tell you I love
the word, "authentic?"

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:01.730
Not.

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:05.710
No, here's the thing--

00:47:05.710 --> 00:47:09.070
I think everybody wants to
find that restaurant that

00:47:09.070 --> 00:47:12.470
is like the paradise.

00:47:12.470 --> 00:47:14.770
There is the grandmother
that's cooking.

00:47:14.770 --> 00:47:19.540
And the rendition of the recipe
is passed on from generation

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:22.360
to generation.

00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:24.040
I can't cook like that.

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:26.710
I have to be
authentic to who I am.

00:47:26.710 --> 00:47:32.350
My experience in
life is not Korea.

00:47:32.350 --> 00:47:35.970
I moved when I was seven, so
I know very little about it.

00:47:35.970 --> 00:47:39.284
And as I grew up, my mom
would never tell me recipes.

00:47:39.284 --> 00:47:40.450
I would go into the kitchen.

00:47:40.450 --> 00:47:43.000
I would taste test for
her, but it was never

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.790
like she was, like,
come on, let's go.

00:47:45.790 --> 00:47:46.840
We're going to cook.

00:47:46.840 --> 00:47:47.980
It was never about that.

00:47:47.980 --> 00:47:51.700
So I got my authentic
experience from the chefs

00:47:51.700 --> 00:47:53.440
that I trained with.

00:47:53.440 --> 00:47:59.680
And from there, me finding my
identity again, back to Korea,

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:01.540
because I was proud.

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:05.380
After I graduated
culinary school,

00:48:05.380 --> 00:48:09.760
my mission was to cook
Asian food the best way

00:48:09.760 --> 00:48:11.110
that I know how--

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:13.090
not Korean food, but Asian food.

00:48:13.090 --> 00:48:16.810
Because that was missing.

00:48:16.810 --> 00:48:20.410
I knew it was missing,
because after I graduated,

00:48:20.410 --> 00:48:26.050
I wanted to find the master, the
sensei, the guy, or the lady,

00:48:26.050 --> 00:48:30.400
that I wanted to learn
everything what they know.

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:32.770
And there was no such person.

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:37.000
And so I started finding
these little techniques

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:40.840
and little skills from
people that I worked for.

00:48:40.840 --> 00:48:46.000
My business plan was to open up
that authentic restaurant that

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:48.050
was authentic to me.

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:52.150
So I'm not going to be the
[INAUDIBLE] the [INAUDIBLE],,

00:48:52.150 --> 00:48:52.900
I can't.

00:48:52.900 --> 00:48:54.640
I don't know how.

00:48:54.640 --> 00:48:57.100
And that's the thing.

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:59.140
I make vegan kimchi.

00:48:59.140 --> 00:49:00.670
That's not traditional.

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:04.240
But I know that's the best
rendition of vegan kimchi

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:08.650
that I know, without using fish
sauce, without using shrimp

00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:11.470
paste, because I'm
listening to my customers.

00:49:11.470 --> 00:49:13.930
Because they're like, well,
I can't eat shellfish.

00:49:13.930 --> 00:49:16.220
I can't eat fish.

00:49:16.220 --> 00:49:17.790
Why can't you do
a vegetarian one?

00:49:17.790 --> 00:49:21.530
Well, we made it
gluten free, vegan,

00:49:21.530 --> 00:49:23.930
and we do our best
version of that.

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:25.480
So is that traditional?

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:26.530
No, it's not.

00:49:26.530 --> 00:49:29.650
But is it pleasing to
the general public?

00:49:29.650 --> 00:49:30.610
Yes, it is.

00:49:30.610 --> 00:49:35.020
So I have to listen to
how a business is run.

00:49:35.020 --> 00:49:39.880
But I have a
conversation with my mom.

00:49:39.880 --> 00:49:42.010
And she makes her own soy sauce.

00:49:42.010 --> 00:49:43.240
Is that traditional?

00:49:43.240 --> 00:49:45.480
No, she has tons of time,
so she could do that.

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:47.730
We cannot, so we have to buy it.

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:51.940
But talking to
her takes me back.

00:49:51.940 --> 00:49:59.180
That tradition of maybe son
to father, mother to daughter,

00:49:59.180 --> 00:50:00.310
mother to son--

00:50:00.310 --> 00:50:03.250
I feel like I'm getting the
authentic version of what

00:50:03.250 --> 00:50:05.710
I'm doing, because I'm
conversing with her.

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:08.320
I'm getting the history of why.

00:50:08.320 --> 00:50:11.950
And from there, we do it
to the general public,

00:50:11.950 --> 00:50:16.570
where we get to take that recipe
that maybe my mom told me,

00:50:16.570 --> 00:50:21.600
and times it by 200, plus
by five days, six days,

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:22.480
seven days.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:26.560
Now that recipe is 1,400
portions of whatever.

00:50:26.560 --> 00:50:28.360
Is that traditional?

00:50:28.360 --> 00:50:28.890
No.

00:50:28.890 --> 00:50:32.140
It has to be commercial
enough for us

00:50:32.140 --> 00:50:34.820
to function as a
restaurant, then go beyond.

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:39.730
So there needs to be a
balance of whose tradition,

00:50:39.730 --> 00:50:43.030
and how you grew up, and
being authentic to who

00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:44.400
you are as a person.

00:50:49.750 --> 00:50:54.040
It hits a spot
with me, because I

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:57.730
can't be authentic
to my tradition,

00:50:57.730 --> 00:51:00.440
because I was kind
of taken away.

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:05.200
So I have to find my own
way to discover where I am,

00:51:05.200 --> 00:51:06.490
and what I'm cooking.

00:51:06.490 --> 00:51:08.290
And this is what I study to do.

00:51:08.290 --> 00:51:14.230
So this is our version
of authentic recipes

00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:16.890
of where we are.

00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:18.430
We do a Thai curry bolognese.

00:51:18.430 --> 00:51:20.650
Is that authentic?

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:22.597
It's not, but I know
what a bolognese

00:51:22.597 --> 00:51:23.680
is supposed to taste like.

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:25.360
I've made bolognese.

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:29.410
But why not take all the
elements of the bolognese,

00:51:29.410 --> 00:51:33.660
and instead of using pork,
we use tea-smoked duck.

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:38.200
Now we have pasta that's
made with [INAUDIBLE] wine

00:51:38.200 --> 00:51:41.320
instead of duck eggs to make it.

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:42.100
Is it lighter?

00:51:42.100 --> 00:51:42.610
Yes it is.

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:43.600
Is it more flavorful?

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:44.870
I think so.

00:51:44.870 --> 00:51:49.380
But it is our rendition
of authentic dishes

00:51:49.380 --> 00:51:53.400
that I get basically
inspired by,

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:55.690
because I love Italian food.

00:51:55.690 --> 00:51:59.140
And we put our spin on it.

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:02.490
So it's very hard
question to answer.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:05.120
But that's the answer
that I could give.

