00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:29.185
AUDIENCE: OK, second question--
just given the spices

00:53:29.185 --> 00:53:33.760
and the richness of the flavors
in Korean food in particular,

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:36.244
is there a particular
type or style of wine

00:53:36.244 --> 00:53:41.970
that you found that pairs well?
or how do you approach that?

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:44.520
BILL KIM: I am not
a huge drinker,

00:53:44.520 --> 00:53:50.160
but when I do different
realms of spices,

00:53:50.160 --> 00:53:56.250
it's usually cut by sauvignon
blanc, or I like to have beer.

00:53:56.250 --> 00:53:59.400
Ros is really good.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:03.660
A margarita is also delicious.

00:54:03.660 --> 00:54:07.780
It's really-- I spent
20 years of my life--

00:54:07.780 --> 00:54:11.790
we would, at Charlie
Trotter, if somebody came in

00:54:11.790 --> 00:54:15.120
to start off their
meal with red wine,

00:54:15.120 --> 00:54:18.150
we would stop what we're doing.

00:54:18.150 --> 00:54:22.530
Then we would have to do
a red wine menu on a dime.

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:24.810
So I get it.

00:54:24.810 --> 00:54:27.960
But for me, it's
really up to you,

00:54:27.960 --> 00:54:29.760
how you want your food to be.

00:54:29.760 --> 00:54:32.300
And the recipe's all about that.

00:54:32.300 --> 00:54:34.560
And if you want
to drink Kool-Aid,

00:54:34.560 --> 00:54:38.400
or if you want to drink
Gatorade, or lemonade,

00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:40.280
it's really up to you.

00:54:40.280 --> 00:54:43.090
And you make that experience,
because we all do it.

00:54:43.090 --> 00:54:46.500
Like my wife, she's very
particular about what

00:54:46.500 --> 00:54:47.190
she drinks.

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:49.710
I'm just, like,
give me an ice tea.

00:54:49.710 --> 00:54:56.310
I'll drink it with a steak, with
maitre-d' butter, and I'm OK.

00:54:56.310 --> 00:55:02.450
It's really up to the individual
what they want to experience.

00:55:02.450 --> 00:55:05.634
And really, it shouldn't
be about the beverage

00:55:05.634 --> 00:55:06.300
you're drinking.

00:55:06.300 --> 00:55:08.970
Obviously, you want it
to be, like, so perfect.

00:55:08.970 --> 00:55:12.430
And those recommendations
with beer, the white,

00:55:12.430 --> 00:55:14.700
and the ros is awesome.

00:55:14.700 --> 00:55:17.640
But it's really you make
your own experience,

00:55:17.640 --> 00:55:19.590
I think, even with the recipe.

00:55:19.590 --> 00:55:22.520
You make it your own experience.

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:25.700
CHANGDRA RAM: He does say,
in the recipe for the chicken

00:55:25.700 --> 00:55:28.850
drumsticks, that he used
to always drink Tang

00:55:28.850 --> 00:55:30.310
with them when he was a kid.

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:30.620
BILL KIM: Tang.

00:55:30.620 --> 00:55:31.190
CHANGDRA RAM: So there's Tang.

00:55:31.190 --> 00:55:32.065
BILL KIM: Yeah, Tang.

00:55:32.065 --> 00:55:34.400
I don't know of
Tang's around, but--

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:34.900
yeah

00:55:34.900 --> 00:55:36.830
SPEAKER: It's the ideal pairing.

00:55:36.830 --> 00:55:40.247
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] given
your sommelier experience?

00:55:40.247 --> 00:55:41.830
CHANGDRA RAM:
Certainly, my experience

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:44.590
is not like a somm
working on the floor.

00:55:44.590 --> 00:55:48.830
I mean, I think what Bill
said is very accurate.

00:55:48.830 --> 00:55:50.447
I drink a lot of--

00:55:50.447 --> 00:55:52.280
I did have to drink
while writing this book.

00:55:54.790 --> 00:56:00.950
I really liked, also, a
lot of pinot gris, I think,

00:56:00.950 --> 00:56:02.730
works really well
with those flavors.

00:56:02.730 --> 00:56:06.170
Viognier, as well, something
that's very sort of fruit

00:56:06.170 --> 00:56:08.810
forward works really
nicely with the spice.

00:56:08.810 --> 00:56:14.510
But also, I think anything
kind of sparkling helps.

00:56:14.510 --> 00:56:18.830
Because it actually cleanses
your palate in between bites.

00:56:18.830 --> 00:56:21.290
So you don't get this
overload from the build-up

00:56:21.290 --> 00:56:25.190
of all of the seasonings kind
of killing your palate there.

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:27.630
So when in doubt, drink a beer.

00:56:27.630 --> 00:56:28.400
BILL KIM: Yeah.

00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:30.274
SPEAKER: OK, well, I
have one final question.

00:56:30.274 --> 00:56:34.010
It's a Q&amp;A on behalf of Greg
on our Caf team for the Food

00:56:34.010 --> 00:56:35.140
Talks program.

00:56:35.140 --> 00:56:36.950
And just a quick plug--

00:56:36.950 --> 00:56:38.990
today's talk is very
much a collaboration

00:56:38.990 --> 00:56:41.839
between the Google Food
Program and Talks at Google.

00:56:41.839 --> 00:56:43.880
And we probably will do
these types of talks just

00:56:43.880 --> 00:56:45.770
to get folks engaged.

00:56:45.770 --> 00:56:47.960
But one of the things
we're thinking about a lot

00:56:47.960 --> 00:56:50.270
on the caf side is
about food waste,

00:56:50.270 --> 00:56:54.050
and how we can reduce that,
and how we can be smarter about

00:56:54.050 --> 00:56:57.380
maybe making something new out
of what was cooked on Monday

00:56:57.380 --> 00:56:58.380
or whatever.

00:56:58.380 --> 00:57:00.440
And you have an entire
chapter dedicated

00:57:00.440 --> 00:57:01.760
to reducing food waste.

00:57:01.760 --> 00:57:03.350
Tell us a little
bit more about that.

00:57:03.350 --> 00:57:04.520
BILL KIM: Yeah.

00:57:04.520 --> 00:57:10.880
I got to be very honest--
my wife hates leftovers.

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:12.530
After two days, she
will not eat it.

00:57:12.530 --> 00:57:13.850
She will not touch it.

00:57:13.850 --> 00:57:15.650
So guess what?

00:57:15.650 --> 00:57:18.560
I always tell her that I got
this from the restaurant,

00:57:18.560 --> 00:57:19.940
or I bought it someplace.

00:57:19.940 --> 00:57:22.340
But it's actually redone.

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.380
I use the leftovers.

00:57:24.380 --> 00:57:29.930
So I think it's
part of cooking that

00:57:29.930 --> 00:57:33.170
is very underutilized,
because to me,

00:57:33.170 --> 00:57:35.300
that's how I
learned how to cook.

00:57:35.300 --> 00:57:38.750
You take spaghetti sauce, and
if you make more than what you

00:57:38.750 --> 00:57:41.280
have, what do you do with it?

00:57:41.280 --> 00:57:43.730
Do you not make spaghetti
with spaghetti sauce?

00:57:43.730 --> 00:57:47.030
No, you could actually
make tomato soup

00:57:47.030 --> 00:57:48.990
by adding, maybe,
a little cream,

00:57:48.990 --> 00:57:52.100
and blending some
basil in there.

00:57:52.100 --> 00:57:54.440
So I love cooking like that.

00:57:54.440 --> 00:57:57.590
And the book is entirely
dedicated to that kind

00:57:57.590 --> 00:57:58.770
of cooking.

00:57:58.770 --> 00:58:05.690
It's not wasting, and being
able to use everything.

00:58:05.690 --> 00:58:07.430
We don't have
bread at the house.

00:58:07.430 --> 00:58:08.240
You know why?

00:58:08.240 --> 00:58:10.520
Because I don't like
bread when it gets stale.

00:58:10.520 --> 00:58:12.050
So we have rice cakes.

00:58:12.050 --> 00:58:15.590
I eat rice cakes like
nobody's business,

00:58:15.590 --> 00:58:17.090
because it doesn't go stale.

00:58:17.090 --> 00:58:21.660
So I'm very practical
about how we use the food.

00:58:21.660 --> 00:58:24.650
So when we buy a
whole chicken, yes, I

00:58:24.650 --> 00:58:27.960
don't turn on my
stove to cook chicken.

00:58:27.960 --> 00:58:30.630
So we buy the
rotisserie chicken.

00:58:30.630 --> 00:58:33.950
So that turns into three meals.

00:58:33.950 --> 00:58:36.642
So the second day, my wife
is at work, and I make soup.

00:58:36.642 --> 00:58:37.350
And she's, like--

00:58:37.350 --> 00:58:38.600
I'm, like, I bought soup.

00:58:38.600 --> 00:58:39.380
Here it is.

00:58:39.380 --> 00:58:42.710
But she doesn't know it's
from the same chicken.

00:58:42.710 --> 00:58:44.690
Then we'll do chicken salad.

00:58:44.690 --> 00:58:46.760
So now we're taking
that chicken so we

00:58:46.760 --> 00:58:48.600
have three recipes out of it.

00:58:48.600 --> 00:58:52.580
So that's how we
like to kind of not

00:58:52.580 --> 00:58:54.920
have food waste at the house.

00:58:54.920 --> 00:58:57.860
Cilantro is used
many different ways.

00:58:57.860 --> 00:58:59.990
And just has to be so you can--

00:58:59.990 --> 00:59:01.370
my wife doesn't know.

00:59:01.370 --> 00:59:03.200
It's like we make pesto.

00:59:03.200 --> 00:59:07.460
We use it in soups, and
sometimes I might add oil.

00:59:07.460 --> 00:59:10.040
But it's just constant.

00:59:10.040 --> 00:59:12.590
Even sometimes when I have
Parmesan cheese left over

00:59:12.590 --> 00:59:18.080
from takeout, that
will go into something.

00:59:18.080 --> 00:59:21.007
But my wife does not know.

00:59:21.007 --> 00:59:21.840
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:59:21.840 --> 00:59:24.972
CHANGDRA RAM: But you're right.

00:59:24.972 --> 00:59:26.930
We do have an entire
chapter in the book that's

00:59:26.930 --> 00:59:29.150
all about how to use leftovers.

00:59:29.150 --> 00:59:32.240
And so there are recipes
for if you happen

00:59:32.240 --> 00:59:39.200
to have some extra
leftover chops,

00:59:39.200 --> 00:59:41.120
or if you have extra
skirt steak, say.

00:59:41.120 --> 00:59:43.220
And the kind of the
worst to approach

00:59:43.220 --> 00:59:47.060
leftovers like that is to say,
I grilled this skirt steak

00:59:47.060 --> 00:59:47.910
two days ago.

00:59:47.910 --> 00:59:51.180
So now I'm going to
eat it the same way,

00:59:51.180 --> 00:59:52.700
and expect that
it's going to taste

00:59:52.700 --> 00:59:55.120
like it did just off the grill.

00:59:55.120 --> 00:59:56.990
But you can thinly slice it.

00:59:56.990 --> 01:00:02.120
You can toss it with some
udon noodles, and maybe

01:00:02.120 --> 01:00:06.200
some of the Korean pesto that's
one of the recipes in the book.

01:00:06.200 --> 01:00:08.540
And suddenly, you're
making it into something

01:00:08.540 --> 01:00:09.860
that's totally different.

01:00:09.860 --> 01:00:13.340
So we have recipes
that Bill created

01:00:13.340 --> 01:00:17.314
that are all about how to
take different leftovers

01:00:17.314 --> 01:00:18.230
from different things.

01:00:18.230 --> 01:00:22.710
Because once you look at
grilled, leftover asparagus

01:00:22.710 --> 01:00:25.196
sitting in your fridge, you've
got to do something to it.

01:00:25.196 --> 01:00:27.570
Because you're not going to
just eat it the way you would

01:00:27.570 --> 01:00:30.930
if it just came off the grill,
but mixed up in a salad, mixed

01:00:30.930 --> 01:00:32.370
up in a sandwich, it's great.

01:00:32.370 --> 01:00:35.250
And so we also created all
these different matrices

01:00:35.250 --> 01:00:41.040
to help guide readers and
users so if you take a protein,

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:42.870
you want to add
a nice veg to it.

01:00:42.870 --> 01:00:44.540
You want to have
some kind of starch.

01:00:44.540 --> 01:00:47.070
And here all these different
examples, and then mix

01:00:47.070 --> 01:00:51.500
and match whatever you've
got in your kitchen,

01:00:51.500 --> 01:00:54.030
so you don't have to go out,
maybe, and find something

01:00:54.030 --> 01:00:57.450
special-- that you
can pull through,

01:00:57.450 --> 01:00:59.760
pull all of your leftovers
out of the fridge,

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:05.625
and create a really cool noodle
bowl, or a salad, or a grain

01:01:05.625 --> 01:01:07.740
bowl, or something
like that based

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:09.090
on what you've got leftover.

01:01:09.090 --> 01:01:11.025
So don't waste anything.

